'''''Opisthorchis felineus''''', or '''cat liver fluke''' is a [[trematode]] [[parasite]] that infects the [[liver]] in mammals. It was first discovered in 1884 in a cat's liver by Sebastiano Rivolta of Italy. In 1891, Russian scientist K.N. Vinogradov found it in a human, and named the parasite a "Siberian liver fluke". In the 1930s, [[helminthology|helminthologist]] [[Hans Vogel (scientist)|Hans Vogel]] of [[Hamburg]] published an article describing the life cycle of ''Opisthorchis felineus''.<ref>[http://www15.bni-hamburg.de/bni/bni2/neu2/getfile.acgi?area_engl=history&pid=132] Bernhard Nocht Institute for Tropical Medicine</ref>

The first "intermediate hosts" of the parasite are [[freshwater snail]]s ''[[Bithynia inflata]]'' (synonym: ''[[Codiella inflata]]''),<ref name="WHO 1995"/> ''[[Bithynia troschelii]]''<ref name="WHO 1995"/> and ''[[Bithynia leachii]]''.<ref name="WHO 1995">[[World Health Organization]] (1995). ''Control of Foodborne Trematode Infection''. WHO Technical Report Series. 849. [http://whqlibdoc.who.int/trs/WHO_TRS_849_(part1).pdf PDF part 1], [http://whqlibdoc.who.int/trs/WHO_TRS_849_(part2).pdf PDF part 2]. page 125-126.</ref> The second "intermediate hosts" are freshwater fish, followed by the final host, which are fish-eating mammals such as felines and humans. It is estimated that 1.5 million people in Russia are infected with the parasite. Inhabitants of Siberia acquire the infection by consuming raw, slightly salted and frozen fish.

Opisthorchiasis, the disease caused by ''Opisthorchis felineus'', ranges in severity from asymptomatic infection to severe illness. Patient outcome is dependent on early detection and treatment.

Human cases of opisthorchiasis may affect the [[liver]], [[pancreas]], and [[gall bladder]]. If not treated in the early stages, opisthorchiasis may cause [[cirrhosis]] of the liver and increased risk of [[Hepatocellular carcinoma|liver cancer]], but may be asymptomatic in children.<ref>[http://www.promedmail.org/pls/promed/f?p=2400:1001:4800346785134245443::::F2400_P1001_BACK_PAGE,F2400_P1001_ARCHIVE_NUMBER,F2400_P1001_USE_ARCHIVE:1001,20031104.2731,Y ProMED-mail | ProMED-mail<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

[[File:Opisthorchis LifeCycle.gif|thumb|left|300px|[[Biological life cycle|Life cycle]] of the cat liver fluke]]

Two weeks after flukes enter the body, the parasites infect the [[biliary tract]]. Symptoms of infection include fever, general malaise, skin rash, and gastrointestinal disturbances. Severe [[anemia]] and liver damage may also incapacitate the infected person for 1-2 months. Treatment of opisthorchiasis is generally with a single dose of [[praziquantel]].<ref>[http://www.promedmail.org/pls/promed/f?p=2400:1001:4800346785134245443::::F2400_P1001_BACK_PAGE,F2400_P1001_ARCHIVE_NUMBER,F2400_P1001_USE_ARCHIVE:1001,20030822.2118,Y ProMED-mail | ProMED-mail<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

